      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the dal",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{rapeseed-oil}} of oil in a saucepan over medium heat. Cook {{onion}} diced onion for 8 minutes until golden. Add {{garlic}} of grated garlic and {{ginger-root}} of grated ginger; cook 2 minutes. Add {{turmeric}} of turmeric, stir, then add {{tomato}} chopped tomatoes. Cook for 5 minutes until broken down. Add {{red-lentils}} of rinsed lentils and 800 ml of water. Bring to a simmer; cook for 20 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the lentils are soft and the dal is thick. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the tarka",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{ghee}} of ghee in a small frying pan over medium-high heat until very hot. Add {{mustard-seeds-black}} of mustard seeds; when they start to pop, add {{cumin-seeds}} of cumin seeds and {{garlic}} of sliced garlic. Fry for 30 seconds until the garlic is golden. Add {{chilli-flakes}} of chilli flakes and remove from the heat immediately. Pour the hot tarka over the dal.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "The tarka takes under a minute from start to finish. Prepare all ingredients before heating the fat; work fast.",
              "cause": "Garlic or spices overcooked in the hot ghee.",
              "symptom": "Tarka bitter and burnt"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add a splash of hot water to loosen. Red lentils absorb a lot of water; check and stir every 5 minutes.",
              "cause": "Cooked too long without enough water.",
              "symptom": "Dal very thick and gluey"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The onion needs a full 8 minutes to develop sweetness. The ghee for the tarka must be smoking-hot before the seeds go in.",
              "cause": "Insufficient onion caramelisation, or tarka not sizzling hot enough.",
              "symptom": "Flat, dull flavour"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Dal in some form is eaten daily across the Indian subcontinent. It ranges from the plainest lentils with turmeric to the rich dal makhani of Punjabi restaurants. Tarka dal sits in the everyday middle: easy to make, cheap, filling, and easy to change with whatever lentils or spices you have. Serve with basmati rice and a flatbread, or alongside a meat curry as the veg.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
